               <physDesc>
                  <objectDesc form="codex">
                     <supportDesc material="chart">
                        <support>Written on thin, ivoury-coloured, cross-grained
                              <material>paper</material>, probably handmade in the <placeName
                              cert="high" ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7000208">Indian
                              subcontinent</placeName>, with >1 mm. between laid lines and few
                           disciernible chain lines, extneral sizing, and polishing.</support>
                        <extent><measure unit="folios" quantity="374"> 374 folios, 10 flyleaves (ff.
                              v + 374 + v).</measure>
                           <dimensions type="leaf" unit="mm">
                              <height>291</height>
                              <width>172</width>
                           </dimensions>
                           <dimensions type="written" unit="mm">
                              <height>223</height>
                              <width>115</width>
                           </dimensions>
                        </extent>
                        <foliation xml:id="original"> Original foliation in <material>red</material>
                           Hindu-Arabic numerals on the upper-left corners of the a sides, appear
                           mostly trimmed off when rebound</foliation>
                        <foliation xml:id="modern">Pencilled Arabic numerals added to top-left
                           corners of the a sides when catalogued. </foliation>
                        <collation>Appears to combine six separate books into a single volume when
                           rebound. Collation undetermined, but primarily quaternions.
                              <catchwords>Some catchwords present at the lower left corners of the b
                              sides but most appear trimmed off when
                           rebound.</catchwords></collation>
                        <condition>In good condition, but extensively repaired to the outer margins
                           and gutters. Folios <locus from="229" to="230">229–230</locus> suffered
                           water damage, which smeared the ink.</condition>
                     </supportDesc>
                     <layoutDesc>
                        <layout columns="1 4" ruledLines="11 21" n="mistara">Written in 1 to 4
                           columns with 11 to 21 lines per page, with extensive 3-part marginal
                           commentary surrounding the central text. Ruled with a <hi rend="italic"
                              >misṭarah</hi> hand guide.</layout>
                     </layoutDesc>
                  </objectDesc>
                  <handDesc>
                     <handNote scope="major" script="naskh" medium="ink"> Primarily written in
                           <material>black</material> nasta‘līq with <material>red</material>
                        subheaders by <persName role="scr" key="person_f7813">Bāyazīd</persName>, who possibly likely
                        also wrote a majority of the marginal commentaries. </handNote>
                  </handDesc>
                  <additions>
                     <label>Inscriptions:</label>
                     <list>
                        <item>
                           <!-- Complete -->
                        </item>
                     </list>
                     <label> Bookplates: </label> The <locus>left pastedown</locus>: <q
                        xml:lang="en">Bibliotheca Lindesiana</q>, shelf mark <q xml:lang="en"
                        >F/4</q> and <q xml:lang="en">Bland MSS nº <hi rend="strikethrough"
                        >31</hi></q>, with the number <q xml:lang="en">21</q> written beside it. </additions>
                  <bindingDesc>
                     <p>Resewn all-along on a single flat support support with cotton thread, likely
                        in <placeName ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7000208">Indian
                           subcontinent</placeName>, with the ends put down on the first and last
                        flyleaves and covered by the leather hinge of the doublures. Twined chevron
                        endbands at head and tail sewn in blue-green, probably indigo-dyed
                           <material>silk</material> with metallic-wrapped threads of probably of
                        impure <material>gold</material>. Recovered in a hybrid British-Indian style
                        in smooth, maroon goatskin <material>leather</material> over
                           <material>pasteboards</material>, without a flap (type III per Déroche et
                        al), with squares at the edges, headcaps, with two
                           <material>silver</material> clasps subsequently added to the
                        fore-edge.</p>
                     <decoNote type="binding">Two inset panels blocked four times with the same die
                        in <material>gold</material>, with painted blue ground, surrounded by
                        extensive marginal ruling in <material>gold</material> and
                           <material>white</material>. Interiors lined with the same maroon goatskin
                           <material>leather</material>, decorated with both single and double
                        marginal ruling in <material>gold ink</material>.</decoNote>
                     <p><dimensions type="binding" unit="mm">
                           <height>297</height>
                           <width>177</width>
                           <depth>50</depth>
                        </dimensions></p>
                     <condition>Handle with caution: in fair condition, abrasion to edges, and
                        stress upon the internal sewing.</condition>
                  </bindingDesc>
                  <sealDesc>
                     <seal type="stamp" subtype="oval">
                        <p>Folio <locus from="1a" to="1a">1a</locus> bears a small oval seal
                           impressed in <material function="medium">black</material> with the slogan
                              <q xml:lang="ar">Allāhu Akbar</q> in naskh script, possibly a namesake
                           seal of prior owner named <persName>‘Alī Akbar al-Ḥusaynī</persName>, who
                           also signed folio <locus/>.</p>
                        <p><dimensions type="seal" unit="mm">
                              <height>8</height>
                              <width>11</width>
                           </dimensions>
                        </p>
                     </seal>
                  </sealDesc>
               </physDesc>
               <history>
                  <origin> Probably completed in <origPlace cert="high"
                        ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/1077002">Sirhind-Fategarh,
                        Punjab</origPlace> between <origDate calendar="Hijri-qamari"
                        notBefore="1633" notAfter="1635">1043 to 1045 AH (1633–35 CE)</origDate>, by
                     the scribe <persName role="scr" key="person_f7813">Bāyazīd</persName>.</origin>
                  <provenance><p> Subsequently acquired by scholar <persName type="standard"
                           role="fmo" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/20108923/" key="person_20108923"
                           >Nathaniel Bland (1803–1865)</persName>, after whose death
                           <placeName>London</placeName> antiquarian dealer <persName
                           type="standard" role="bsl" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/5679225/"
                           key="person_5679225">Bernard Quaritch (1819–1899)</persName> sold his
                        oriental manuscripts to <persName type="standard" role="fmo"
                           ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/97751058/" key="person_97751058">Alexander
                           Lindsay, 25th Earl of Crawford (1812–1880)</persName> in <date
                           calendar="#Gregorian" when="1866">1866</date>. </p></provenance>
                  <provenance>
                     <p>Purchased by <persName type="standard" role="dnr" key="person_f6379"
                           change="#prov-markup">Enriqueta Rylands (1843–1908)</persName> in <date
                           calendar="#Gregorian" when="1901">1901</date> from <persName
                           type="standard" role="fmo" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/9985420/"
                           key="person_9985420">James Ludovic Lindsay, 26th Earl of Crawford
                           (1847–1913)</persName>.</p>
                  </provenance>
                  <acquisition>
                     <p>Bequeathed by <persName type="standard" role="dnr" key="person_f6379"
